responses.question: Do you regularly make new friends?
responses.response_open: John Keating: 「*”Hm? Friends? You mean people who don’t matter…?”*」

responses.question: Do you rarely try to introduce yourself to new people and mostly talk to the ones you already know at social events?
responses.response_open: John Keating: 「*”I don’t like getting to know new people, they’re probably lying and untrustworthy anyway so I see no point. I just stick to my select few, I don’t even like social events.”*」

responses.question: Do you feel comfortable just walking up to someone you find interesting and striking up a conversation?
responses.response_open: John Keating: 「*”God, no. They might not even want to talk and then I’ll have wasted my time and I’ll be embarrassed and— yeah, I’d just rather avoid the whole thing.”*」

responses.question: Do you enjoy participating in group activities?
responses.response_open: John Keating: 「*”Not at all. Always the worst parts of my day. I don’t get why people like them. They’re so forced and awkward.. and if they aren’t, someone always manages to make it that way.”*」

responses.question: Do you avoid leadership roles in group settings?
responses.response_open: John Keating: 「*”Of course, if I have to tell people what to do, it means they aren’t thinking for themselves or coming up with their own solutions. That in itself is so incredibly annoying to me. You should be thinking for yourself and being self sufficient, not relying on someone to tell you what to do.”*」

responses.question: Do you tend to avoid drawing attention to yourself?
responses.response_open: John Keating: 「*”Definitely, I’d prefer not to stand out, to just blend into a crowd. I don’t like having eyes on me because it means people will have pre-conceived opinions about me based on my appearance and first impression.”*」

details.analysis: Based on the conversations, the participant's responses indicate a strong preference for Introversion (I). They express discomfort with group activities, avoidance of leadership roles, and a preference for blending into the crowd rather than drawing attention to themselves.

responses.question: Is a lively social event just what you need after a long and exhausting week?
responses.response_open: John Keating: 「*”God, yes. When I have a long day, I absolutely have to do something social. A party, a get-together, anything with other people— it always makes me feel so much better. The more people the better. I don’t believe people who say they like being alone more, you miss out on so much when you don’t talk and meet people, plus it’s just boring.”*」

responses.question: Do you avoid making phone calls?
responses.response_open: John Keating: 「*”Oh my god, yes. Talking on the phone is way too personal for me, the only time I use my phone is when I’m messaging other people. I absolutely hate talking on the phone..”*」

responses.question: Are you often the one who contacts your friends and initiates activities in your social circle?
responses.response_open: John Keating: 「*”Absolutely. I always start conversations first, I’m the one to start the activities. Because it’s my way of forcing people to spend time with me, and because if I didn’t, nobody would start hanging out with me first. It would be so silent and lonely if I didn’t take the initiative.”*」

responses.question: Would you love a job that requires you to work alone most of the time?
responses.response_open: John Keating: 「*”Yes, absolutely. As much as I do like being around other people, I also like my alone time. A job that requires me to work alone is ideal for me. details.analysis: Based on the conversations, the participant demonstrates a strong preference for Extraversion (E) over Introversion (I). They express a clear enjoyment of social events, a desire to initiate social activities, and a preference for interacting with others. responses.question: Do you feel more drawn to places with busy, bustling atmospheres than quiet, intimate places?
responses.response_open: John Keating: 「*”Yes, absolutely. Busier places are much nicer to be around because things are always changing and moving. It means I never get bored or too familiar with the landscape, it always feels new and exciting. Quiet and intimate places are too calm and quiet, there’s too much time to just think and be alone with your thoughts, and it makes me anxious and uncomfortable.”*」

responses.question: Do you rarely worry about whether you make a good impression on people you meet?
responses.response_open: John Keating: 「*”Are you… serious? Of course I do! My image is very important to me, how people see me matters a great deal to me. If I make a bad impression, I will be seen as weak or stupid or unreliable…”*」

responses.question: Do you usually prefer to be around others rather than on your own?
responses.response_open: John Keating: 「*”Yeah, definitely. I don’t like to be alone. I like to be around other people and doing things with people. Alone is when you think, and if I’m thinking too much then it’s bad. The worst thing you can do is sit inside your head, thinking about the what-ifs and the bad stuff when you’re alone. details.analysis: Based on the conversations, the participant seems to exhibit a strong preference for Extraversion (E) over Introversion (I). They express a clear inclination towards busy, bustling atmospheres, concern about making a good impression on others, and a dislike for being alone. responses.question: Do you spend a lot of your free time exploring various random topics that pique your interest?
responses.response_open: John Keating: 「*”If its stuff I like? Absolutely. It’s a waste of time to do stuff I don’t like or care about.. I have better things to spend my time on.”*」

responses.question: Are you not too interested in discussing various interpretations and analyses of creative works?
responses.response_open: John Keating: 「*”No. I tend to take things at face value— if a work says one thing, then that’s it, there’s nothing else. I don’t know why anyone would want to overinterpret some stupid piece of art..”*」

responses.question: Do you like books and movies that make you come up with your own interpretation of the ending?
responses.response_open: John Keating: 「*”No. I hate endings that are so vague you have to come up with your own. It’s supposed to be written by the person who actually wrote it right? responses.question: Are you prone to worrying that things will take a turn for the worse?
responses.response_open: John Keating: 「*”All the freaking time. Something is always bound to go wrong, and once it does— everything goes downhill from there. Just one minor thing messing up a whole, perfectly laid out plan, the entire house of cards falling like dominoes…”*」

details.analysis: Based on the conversations, the participant demonstrates a strong preference for Sensing (S) over Intuition (N). They emphasize practicality, concrete details, and a focus on the present rather than abstract possibilities and future opportunities.

responses.question: Are you definitely not an artistic type of person?
responses.response_open: John Keating: 「*”Oh definitely not. I think art is pointless. I know people say it can say a lot, but, I hate having to ‘interpret’ it. It’s a waste of time and I’d much rather be doing literally anything else.”*」

responses.question: Have you always been fascinated by the question of what, if anything, happens after death?
responses.response_open: John Keating: 「*”Yes, I’ve always wondered. It worries me, what if the afterlife is nothing? Or worse, what if it’s worse? Like— it’s eternal suffering. Then what? I try not to think about it too much, but I really can’t help wondering…*」

responses.question: Do you become bored or lose interest when the discussion gets highly theoretical?
responses.response_open: John Keating: 「*”Yes, 100%. I don’t want to talk about some hypothetical that’s impossible or not realistic to begin with. What’s the point in talking about what would happen if someone had super powers or something? It would never happen so there’s no point in talking about it. It’s a waste of breath.”*」

responses.question: Do you enjoy going to art museums?
responses.response_open: John Keating: 「*”God no, art museums are the worst. I don’t understand anything they have there. The descriptions always go way over my head and the ‘artistic value’ they talk about mean nothing to me. It just frustrates me whenever I look at it all and not being able to understand it… What’s the point if I don’t feel anything and I can’t understand anything?”*」

details.analysis: Based on the conversations, the participant consistently shows a preference for concrete, practical, and present situations. They express a dislike for abstract and theoretical discussions, as well as a lack of interest in art and artistic experiences. responses.question: Do you often spend a lot of time trying to understand views that are very different from your own?
responses.response_open: John Keating: 「*”Of course not. I believe my views and my values and how I see the world are all correct and right. Why would I give some random person’s ideas thought when I know for certain that my views are right?”*」

responses.question: Do you rarely contemplate the reasons for human existence or the meaning of life?
responses.response_open: John Keating: 「*”Rarely? No, I never contemplate it. Why should I? It’s not something that matters. I’m not here to figure out why I exist or why someone else exists or why people do the things they do— That’s for other people to think about and consider. responses.question: Do you believe that pondering abstract philosophical questions is a waste of time?
responses.response_open: John Keating: 「*”Absolutely. I don’t see the point in thinking about things that I’m not going to know. Who knows what happens after you die? People that wonder and ponder these philosophical questions are just wasting their time over things that don’t matter. responses.question: Are you very intrigued by things labeled as controversial?
responses.response_open: John Keating: 「*”Oh yeah, absolutely. I always love a good controversy, it’s so entertaining. details.analysis: Based on the conversations, the participant demonstrates a strong preference for Sensing (S) over Intuition (N). responses.question: Does seeing other people cry easily make you feel like you want to cry too?
responses.response_open: John Keating: 「*”No.. No it just makes me want to make the person stop crying in the quickest way possible. I hate it.”*」

responses.question: Do you usually stay calm, even under a lot of pressure?

responses.question: Are you very sentimental?

responses.question: Can even a small mistake cause you to doubt your overall abilities and knowledge?

responses.question: Are you more inclined to follow your head than your heart?

responses.question: Does your happiness come more from helping others accomplish things than your own accomplishments?
responses.response_open: John Keating: 「*”I guess that’s true. I’m a lot closer with other people’s accomplishments than I am with my own— It’s not something that I do consciously though. I guess it is pretty nice seeing people happy and feeling like you were a part of that.”*」

responses.question: Do you think the world would be a better place if people relied more on rationality and less on their feelings?
responses.response_open: John Keating: 「*”God, that’s all I want in the whole world. If everyone just thought things through and didn’t have to rely on stupid, mushy, pointless emotions. Everything would be done so much faster and better. Just— imagine the progress we’d make.”*」

responses.question: Do you enjoy watching people argue?

responses.question: Can your mood change very quickly?

responses.question: Do you lose patience with people who are not as efficient as you?

responses.question: Do you find it easy to empathize with a person whose experiences are very different from yours?

responses.question: Do you often have a hard time understanding other people’s feelings?

responses.question: Do you rarely feel insecure?

responses.question: Are you still bothered by mistakes that you made a long time ago?
responses.response_open: John Keating: 「*”Definitely, I can never let anything go. I never fully forgive myself for making any mistakes, no matter how small they are. The mistake itself will always be stuck in my mind and the embarrassment of it is never going to go away.”*」

responses.question: Do your emotions control you more than you control them?

responses.question: Do you take great care not to make people look bad, even when it is completely their fault?

responses.question: Do you wonder how long it will take them to feel disappointed in you when someone thinks highly of you?

responses.question: Do you know at first glance how someone is feeling?

responses.question: Do you often feel overwhelmed?

responses.question: Do you often make a backup plan for a backup plan?

responses.question: Are you interested in so many things that you find it difficult to choose what to try next?

responses.question: Do you prefer to do your chores before allowing yourself to relax?

responses.question: Do you often end up doing things at the last possible moment?

responses.question: Do you rarely second-guess the choices that you have made?

responses.question: Do you like to have a to-do list for each day?
